    <section class="how" aria-label="How it works">
      <h2><img class="octo-mini" src="logo.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />How it works</h2>
      <p class="sub">A simple write path you can explain on a whiteboard: append to WAL, stage in memory, flush to
        sorted tables, and compact in the background.</p>

      <div class="steps" aria-label="Write path steps">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="n"><span class="badge">1</span> Write path</div>
          <strong>Append to WAL</strong>
          <p>Durability starts with write ahead logging. Fsync policy is configurable for your risk/throughput needs.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="n"><span class="badge">2</span> In memory</div>
          <strong>Update memtable</strong>
          <p>In memory staging keeps the common path fast and predictable while batching work efficiently.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="n"><span class="badge">3</span> On disk</div>
          <strong>Flush to SSTables</strong>
          <p>Sorted immutable tables make reads and scans efficient and keep file formats straightforward.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="step">
          <div class="n"><span class="badge">4</span> Background</div>
          <strong>Compact</strong>
          <p>Compaction keeps space under control and maintains read performance without requiring constant tuning.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

